introduction.p:
Suppose that you are interested in the values of some function f(x) for x near some fixed point a. When the function is a polynomial or a rational function we can use some arithmetic (and maybe some hard work) to write down the answer. For example:
f(x) &= \frac{x^2-3}{x^2-2x+4}
f(1/5) &= \frac{ \frac{1}{25}-3}{\frac{1}{25}-\frac{2}{5}+4 } = \frac{\frac{1-75}{25} }{\frac{1-10+100}{25}}
&= \frac{-74}{91}
Tedious, but we can do it. On the other hand if you are asked to compute \sin(1/10) then what can we do? We know that a calculator can work it out
\sin(1/10) &= 0.09983341\dots
but how does the calculator do this? How did people compute this before calculators Originally the word calculator referred not to the software or electronic (or even mechanical) device we think of today, but rather to a person who performed calculations. ? A hint comes from the following sketch of \sin(x) for x around 0.

